    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Currently, the type testing functions in the `inspect` module reject the corresponding Cython functions.\r\n\r\nOn the one hand, this makes sense because Cython functions have no byte code, for example, and are therefore not 100% compatible, depending on what users intend to find out when they do the type test.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, this is unfortunate, because many use cases do not require byte code but rely only on certain other features that Cython already emulates.\r\n\r\nLet's discuss if it should stay that way.\r\n\r\nRelevant links:\r\n- http://docs.cython.org/en/latest/src/userguide/limitations.html#inspect-support\r\n- python-trio/trio/issues/550",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Hey there. \r\nThe python community gave the new guideline in [PEP 575](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0575/#cfunction) as the new standard for what a function should be and what kind of functions should exist.\r\nUnfortunately they kicked the cython function from the inspect module without providing the inspect.isbasefunction as mentioned in the document. \r\nSo maybe someone knows what is actually needed to comply with the new standard? \r\n\"Just\" rename \"cyfunction\" to \"cfunction\"? =) \r\nBut then there are also bound methods...\r\n\r\n",
            "created_at": "2019-10-22T18:51:40Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/2609#issuecomment-545102636",
